opening_comment: The name of this peak is INCORRECTLY shown in several open source maps as 'The Woolworths Building'. The correct name of this dramatic rocky peak is 'Woolworth Building', after the famous New York skyscraper it resembles from a certain angle. The error no doubt stems from the fact that there is a retail chain in South Africa called 'Woolworths', and whoever first added the name of this feature is unaware that it was originally and historically named after the skyscraper, not the retail chain! There are many references to 'Woolworth Building' and adventures and misadventures on it in the Journals of The Mountain Club of South Africa, of which I am long-standing member of the Cape Town Section.

Strawberry Hill Farm is not a strawberry farm! The name comes from the wild strawberries that used to grow here. The farm is part of the original Grootvadersbosch Moodie estate, which has been in the Moodie family since the 1800s.¬†‚ÄãThe farm is surrounded by indigenous forest and is a magical place to mountain bike, trail run, swim, kloof, read a book or learn about the inspiring conservation projects that are taking place in the area. The farm is on the boundary of the¬†Grootvadersbosch Nature Reserve¬†and is part of the¬†Grootvadersbosch Conservancy.¬†The property is slowly being restored to indigenous vegetation, with a focus on forest restoration. Existing small pine plantations and rough growing blackwood are being harvested and replaced with indigenous species.  Aileen and Walter moved from the bustle of Cape Town to the Grootvadersbosch Valley 2 years ago. ¬†Aileen's is the third generation of the Moodie family to be living in the valley.¬†  Walter¬†is passionate about building awesome mountain bike trails. He has two engineering degrees with a masters in renewable energy. The farm's energy is partly solar generated and more panels will come on line soon. Walter manages the farm sawmill, develops renewable energy projects and mostly builds mountain bike trails. Walter is Belgian and speaks Flemish, Dutch, French, German, English, Afrikaans, Spanish and a bit of Thai.¬†  Aileen¬†is passionate about riding her bike on Walter's awesome trails and raising funds to build more. She has 2 environmental master's degrees with a focus on water resource management but much prefers spending her time managing the¬†Grootvadersbosch Conservancy¬†and keeping 132 rural people employed in environmental projects.¬†Aileen and Walter¬†both continue to be involved in water and energy projects through their company¬†crossflowconsulting. closing_comment: I added smoothness=very_bad a while ago (implying that cars with high clearance and light-duty off-road vehicles will be able to cope, anything less rugged probably can't).  This was based on various news reports: although I passed through the area in January 2015, I decided it best not to chance that stretch myself!  I don't that there's much else that can be done.  Someone else already added a 20 km/h max speed (also seems valid from various news sources), so I'd be very surprised if routing engines aren't avoiding it.
